How it works:

1. **Gradient computation** (`compute_point_gradients`): for each of the 260,774 wall points, finds its 8 nearest neighbors in 3D and fits a local linear model by least squares to estimate ∇ρ_mean and ∇σ_ρ. Done once, since the mesh is identical across all simulations.
2. **Feature vector per point** (16 features): coordinates (3), normals (3), mean_rho, std_rho, gradient of the mean (3 components + magnitude), gradient magnitude of the std, and the 3 flight conditions.
3. **Target**: `rho − mean_field` rather than raw rho, so LightGBM only learns the condition-dependent deviation.
4. **Training set**: 20,000 randomly sampled points per training simulation (~7M rows for ~350 sims) — full 91M rows would be slow and mostly redundant. A single LightGBM with 2000 trees and 255 leaves trains on this in reasonable time on 10 CPUs.
5. **Prediction**: full field per test sim, adding the mean field back, saved to `y_pred1_gradlgbm.npy`/`y_pred2_gradlgbm.npy`, then evaluated with the same `evaluate_phase` as everything else. It also prints feature importances so you can see whether the gradient features actually get used.
